title: Lanthorn Tower
description: Lanthorn Tower is the second largest tower. It was constructed between 1238 and 1272 by King Henry III and was then connected to Wakefield Tower. The name of the tower comes from its use as a marker to nearby ships along the Thames via a lantern that was lit here each night in the top turret. The original tower was destroyed by a fire in 1774 and rebuilt in 1851.

title: Tower Hill Underground Station (entrance)
description:
Tower Hill is the nearest underground station to the Tower of London and Fenchurch Street station, as well as Tower Gateway DLR (closed as of Summer 2008). It is served by the Circle and District Lines. There are 2 main platforms and a west-facing bay platform used by some District line trains.

In 1882, a station opened on this site called Tower of London. It closed 2 years later and was replaced by a larger station at Mark Lane, when the line was connected up to form the Circle Line. By the 1960s, Mark Lane was far too small and crowded and there was little space to expand it so the larger present day station was opened in 1967. Since then, a new entrance has been opened here with the original entrance now an exit only.

urlhtml: The Grand Palais Yiddish Theatre (site of)
title: The Grand Palais Yiddish Theatre (site of)
description:
The Grand Palais closed as a theatre in 1960 to become a bingo hall.  Sadly in post war Britain the number of Yiddish speakers started to decline dramatically, this coupled to other forms of entertainment (cinema etc) and the migration away from the east end of London by many of the more elderly (and therefore last remaining Yiddish speakers) jewish population resulted in the closure of the theatre.  The building became a Bingo hall which only lasted another 10 years. It closed altogether in 1970.

As of January 2009 a company called Flick Fashions now occupies the former premises of the Grand Palais Yiddish Theatre.  Nothing remarkable in that you may think, but it is entirely indicative of the way life continues in the east end of London.  At the turn of the 20th century east London became the settling point for many jewish families who emigrated to escape persecution in their old homeland.  In the late 1950's and early 1960's Jewish immigrants were being replaced by immigrants from Bangladesh, India and Pakistan.  Today these immigrants and their children live in the same area of East London as the early Jewish communities.  The next wave of immigration into east London coming from the former eastern europe will probably see these buildings being put to a new use some time in the future.

The theatre also had a brief moment of extra fame when it was featured in a documentry entitled "The London nobody knows" staring James Mason as a guide around some of Londons lesser known parts.
